Ruskin, Tolstoy, and Thoreau and how, a generation later, a mature Gandhi’s thought and action challenged modernity’s hegemony. Moreover, the Rudolphs argue that Gandhi’s critique of modern civilization in his 1909 book Hind Swaraj was an opening salvo of the postmodern era and that his theory and practice of nonviolent collective action (satyagraha) articulate and exemplify a postmodern understanding of situational truth. This radical interpretation of Gandhi's life will appeal to anyone who wants to understand Gandhi’s relevance in this century, as well as students and scholars of politics, history, charismatic leadership, and postcolonialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAsceticismxPolitical aspectszIndia. 0aCourage. 0aDemocratizationxPolitical aspectszIndia. 0aPostmodernismxPolitical aspectszIndia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agandhi, postmodernism, tradition, influence, india, london, biography, history, philosophy, activism, politics, nonfiction, modernity, thoreau, ruskin, tolstoy, hind swaraj, civilization, nonviolent collective action, protest, social change, satyagraha, situational truth, postcolonialism, charismatic leadership, democratization, asceticism, public sphere, habermas, self-control, courage, agency.1 aHoeber Rudolph, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRudolph, Lloyd I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRudolph, Susanne Hoeber, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022673123040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226731315423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226731315/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  Universi